              <div class="quotetitle">LordHunter317 wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Despite all of that, it doesn't change that you should treat the raw data as the most important thing, even though it may be (will be) imperfect and incorret.</div><br /><br />There's always measurement error, but it's still closer to reality than anything else you have.<br /><br />That said, there may be points of biased data corruption elsewhere in your data processing chain, and consistency checks can be quite useful for that.

              

              
              
